\nRutland Herald.\nYou're quite right. And what you\ny applie particularly to thoe col\nr release at some future days a\niie-un aimoi pntnpTninr wnicn hi\nady bas taken place. For inMance.\nreceived a story about the election\nlootbail captain that bad a Ires. It\nken place, the copy being aocom\nnied with the inatmctiona to bild\ntil a certain date, which, by the way,\n\ntum there was for bottling up the\nsrs which bad already bappetrl we\nlid not nnleaa it was to rwni\nia!e antre e-kly newapapcr ptiS\nhed ia th town aibere th nVt?f\nlocated A da;ly tewpaper w1Tr\npublak the srers bea it ia neat;\nTHIS IS OVERCOAT\nWEEK\nCome and storm our\nportals if youa want\nthe best storm over\ncoat for man or boy.\nYou know there's been\na mild hurricane\namong the clothing\nmanufacturers.\nHigh prices have tak\nen a tumble.\nEvery Overcoat now\n33 1-3 off regular price.\nA few Boys' Over\ncoats, just seven left,\nat the same reductions.\nMackinaws, too,\nmen and boys.\nfor\nF. H. Rogers\nCompany\nand for our part we hold that in this\ncase it was news when the election\ntook place. Therefore, we felt perfect\nly justified in printing the story when\nthe copy was received. The release date\non such stuff as that is unreasonable.\nCURRENT COMMENT\nBusiness Depression.\nBusiness depression is felt more or\nless in all. sectiona of Vermont. The\nliberal spending of money that has\nprevailed for the past two Years is\nreaching its limit. Manufacturers,\nmerchants and producers are retrench\ning to meet the change that is gradu\nally coming with the return of normal\nconditions. This falling of prices must\ncome to all and the gradual adjust\nment will bring it about without that\ncalamity that so often comes when in\nflated prices drop and the great in\ndustries of the country return to\nstabilized conditions. Newport Ex\npress.\nStill Guessing About That Church.\nThe Barre Times last week had a\nhalf tone of a church in that city. A\ncaption under it read, \"Do you recog\nnize this building? Then help to us\nto fill it.\" Very clever, we say.\nNorthfleld Xews.\nThe church above referred to does\nnot look like any in Barre City, to\nthe writer. We may be wrong but\nwe have a belief we could locate that\nsacred building. However, the News\n:s right about the adv. It's \"clever.\"\nOther church societies would find it\nwell to do likewise. Newport Ex\npress. 40-Pound Does and Fingerling Trout.\nA contemporary notes in its news\ncolumns the prowess of \"one miphty\nhunter who shot a 40-pound doe.\" It\nis just such irresponsibility of a cer\ntain element that is likelv to be\nfound in an exhibition ol similar\nsportsmanship aeainst fingerling trout\nnext summer. While his kill may be\nno breach of the letter of the law, it\ncertainly is against the spirit of the\nCapital\nSavings Bank\nand Trust Co.\nMonlpelier, Vt.\nTo Depositors:\nSafety of principal is\nmore to be desired than\nhigh rates of interest\nSome of our invest\nments\n$440,000 U. S. Liberty\nand Victory Bonds\n$30,000 State of Ver\nmont Bonds\n$75,000 City of Monl\npelier Notes\n4 Per Cent raid on\nSavings Deposits\nBankinjr by Mail Safe\nand Satisfactory\nGEO. L. BLAxVOTAKn. Pre\nI RANK X. 6.U1TH. Treasurer\nTTTTITT\nI\ni i ii ii\nII\n\"Right Makes Might.\"\nThis strong national bank is closing another fiscal year of serv\nice and as we look back upon the days that are past, we are grat\nified in the thought that the safe and conservative policy adopt\ned by those in charge of this bank h?.s enabled us to give a max\nimum of service through good times and bad.\nWe can give assurance to all that the same policy which has\nbrought such a large increase of business to us during the past\nyear will be continued through the next.\nWhen you think of your bank, you should have the feeling that\nyou are doing business with a strong, clean, dependable institu\ntion, an institution with a feeling of responsibility to those whom\nit serves.\nThere never was a time in the history of this bank when this\nfeeling of responsibility was so keenly felt as it is to-day.\nThis bank is not conducted in the interests of those on the\nboard of directors, it is not conducted in the interests of any par\nticular customer or group of customers, but is it conducted in the\ninterests of all the people.\nWhether you do business with this bank or with some other\nbank, you may feel free at all times to come to us for any legiti\nmate banking service or for advice regarding your financial af\nfairs. We shall approach your problems only in the spirit of co\noperation and you may rest assured that whatever you confide to\nus will be held in the strictest confidence.\nWith us, business is business, and the correct way is the only\nway. Those immortal words of Lincoln never had a truer or\nmore fitting application than they present to the conduct of our\nfinancial instituutions to-day.\n\"Right makes might\"; this is the motto of the Peoples National\nBank for the year 1921.\n3\nThe Peoples National Bank\nOFFICERS\nF. D. LADD, President W. C. JOHNSON, JR., Uashier\nW. M. HOLDEN. Vice-President F. K. BEARD, Asst. Cashier\nDIRECTORS\nF. D. Ladd W. M. Holden W. D. Smith A. J. Young\nC. W. Averill F. L. Sargent W. C. Johnson, Jr.\nDeposits made on or before January 13 will draw interest from\nJanaury 1 at 4 per cent.\nScores! Yes! Hundreds!\nare now enrolled as members\nof our\n1921\nChris\ntmas\nThrift Glu\nb\n.25 per week\n.50 per week\n$1.00 per week\n$2.00 per week\n$5.00 per week\nThere are joys awaiting them\nwhen the distribution of\nthousands of dollars is made.\nARE YOU TO BE ONE OF\nTHEM?\nDON'T WAIT! Step in and\nsee us about it, NOW\nNotice!\nThe QUARRY SAVINGS BANK TRUST COMPANY will\nbe pleased to assist depositors of the Barre Savings Bank and\nTrust Co. in proving their claims against that institution. May\nwe suggest that books be left with us to be presented to the Re\nceiver for proof. This will facilitate the work and relieve credi\ntors of the necessity of their personal attention.\nOUARRY SAVINGS BANK\nAND TRUST CO.\nBarre. Vermont.\nBEN A. EASTMAN, President\nH. J. M. JONES Vice-President.\nDIRECTORS\nBen A. Eastman James M. Boutwell W. G. Reynolds\nH. J. M. Jones. B. W. Hooker\nC. M. WILLEY, Treasurer.\nH. F. Cutler E. L. Scott\nH. H. Jackson\nstatutes and the better judgment of\nmost hunters to slaughter a forty\npound doe \"hardly larger than a dog.\"\nAll but himself and his ilk will call it\ndownright cruelty. Middlebury Register.\nState Constabulary.\nCrime waves always generate waves\nof alleged protection from crime. Such\na wave is sure to follow the attempted\nsuppression of rrimes in many cities of\nthe country. In Connecticut the wave\nof lesser crimes in the form of maraud\ning farm crops has become so serious\nthe grangers of that state are advocat\ning the ectablishmpnt of a state con\nstabulary for the protection of crops in\nthe rural districts, snd it is expected\nthe state grange at its annual session\nin January will endorse the scheme and\nintroduce 'a bill to that effe in the\nlegislature.\nIt is said that farmers througbout\nthat srtate have suffered greatly from\nthe theft of their fruit and produce\ncrops but no vigorous attempt to check\nthe thieves has been undertaken. The\nplan for a state constabulary is the\nfirst attempt to bring about a sys\ntematic effort to prevent the raiding of\nfarmer' crops. There seems to b? no\nreason why the fanners should not be\nprotected even if it ia expensive. The\nexpense is only an indication of the se\nriousnem of this form of robbery.\nIt will be strange with the preva\nlence of homicide in Vermont if the\ncoming legislature ia not aked to form\na constabulary for this state. Murders\nare committed In many different sec\nlions of the state and each suspected\nmurder calls for the employment of\nBoston detectives Jo ferret out the guil\nty parties and their appearance in\ncourt to attempt their conviction. lair\ning the ten years from 1!00 to 19rt. in\nclusive, this\" detective service has cot\nthe state from .V.V1 05 to Mfl.H7.VA0\nper year. That it will be lanre for th\npast two year is certain becsu.e of\nthe larje number of bnmicidrs during\nthat period. Brattleboro Reformer.\nUp to Date.\nWife The ice man ay we mut\npay up before he leaves us any more\nice.\nHub Frrarrn credit, eh! Boston\nTranrript.\nCrowding Father Time.\nIt wa an Irih number of Parlia\nment who. MWaUt wearied with the\nl -KC dehele. id\nIf ten -a r thu quetk n to ti f\"r\nthroe rear are win aettle it to morrow\nh-.g B\"tn Tran7 t-\nRANDOLPH\nMr. and Mrs. Rex Fullam of Mont\npelier arrived here Friday for a few\ndays' visit with the lattcr's parents,\nMr. and Mrs. Seldon Tewkbury.\nFrank and William Plumlev went\nto Hart land the last of the week toi\nvisit their sister, who resides there.\nThe Green Mountain Cilove factory\nhas closed down till January 6, and\nmany of the employes have gone to\ntheir homes.\nMrs. Louvan Rogers, who resides at\nJudge Howell's, left here Saturday for\nNorwich, where her son and family re\nside. Mrs. J. C. Alden went to Rethel Sat\nurday to pass the day with relatives.\nOn Sunday morning her daughter, Mrs.\nE. F. Bij'by, a teacher in Newark, N.\nJ., arrived to pafs the vacation with\nber mother and will return after New\nYear's.\nMiss Bertha Manney of Boston ar\nrived here Friday morning to pass the\nrieit few days \"with her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. John Manney.\nThere was a general closing down of\nbusiness over Saturday. At the differ\nent churches the day was observed on\nFriday evening, when tha Sunday\nschoof in each cae gave exercises ap\npropriate to the occasion.\nRev. F. S. Tolman wss in Boston\non Saturday with hit parenta, and Sun\nday the Baptist and Methodist\nchurches united in a service, Rev. R. II.\nMoore being the speaker. The union\nsen-ice wan held at the Bethany\nchurch in the evening, with Rev. R. H.\nMiH.re for the speaker.\nAt the last meeting of the West\nRandolph granee, it was necessary to\nelect three officers to fill vacancies\ncaused bv the resignation of thoe\nelected, the ballots reaulted in II. W.\nHolden as master, Mrs. (ieorp Allen\nx. a i j IT ..x I J\na n vrren ana i,iauve ra.n a. iaj\nassistant stewara. .-ine ranaaaies\nwere elected to membership and reports\nof the officers were given. The lectur\ner arranged for the following program,\nand gave a report of the etate grange;\nZatae B'a r gave a lanjo aolo with\nencore: Mrs. L. Carrigan read a\nChristmas selection, and tJrorg C\nFlint read some rerac paying his re\nsperU to the lecturer. It was voted to\ninvite Clarence Martin of Rochester to\ninstall the officer at the first meeting\nin January.\nThe ladies of Bethany Guild recently\nreal zed frv-ro a a-e epmns. fanry\nartie'es ar.d food and candy. tHZ .W.\nMr and Mrs. J T. 'pe- and n of\nXfwlbf.e'd came Saturday t visit Mr.\nand Mr. H. O. Ranker.\nTI, arrival of eift caHoads ef ksrd j\nrrl lat week ka secured fc(h coal\nfor Randolph for several weeks. Sever\nal more carloads are known to be on\nthe way.\nMr. and Mrs. Pouglaa Barclay and\nchildren of Barre came Friday and were\nthe gues of the latter' parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. Bvron Manchester.\nA Modern Courtship.\nShe One more question.\nH,jYes, dear, I am listening.\nShe Will you love me when I'm\nold?\nHe Well-er this is a practical age,\nvou know, dear. At any rate. 1 11 see\nthat vou get adequate alimony. Bos\nton \"Transcript.\nThey'll Give You Real Wear\nBoth these \"Ball-Band\" Rubber\n.Shoes have leather tons. The\nribbed foot of the smaller shoe is\nheavy gum. The rubber foot of\nthe higher shoe is reinforced with\nheavy duck.\nCome in and let us show you these\nstrongly made, long-wearing shoes.\nYou'll find any other Rubber Foot\nwear you may need in our com\nplete \"Ball-Band\" stock.\nBALLQBAWD'\nW1\n0? I\n1 ll J L xf II 1 \"t. r J t)x.rt Tl.a i\nri' V r Lr Mork on Oil I\nLr. i\nThe House of Your Best\nFriend\nThe best friend a man can have is hia own\nmoney that he has